00:32:58.902 --> 00:33:02.342
treatment response and guiding trial design in

566
00:33:02.442 --> 00:33:05.562
ALK-rearranged non-small cell lung cancer.

567
00:33:06.022 --> 00:33:06.462
Intriguing.

568
00:33:08.782 --> 00:33:09.802
Take it away.

569
00:33:11.162 --> 00:33:20.002
Thank

570
00:33:20.022 --> 00:33:23.902
you for the introduction. On behalf of my co-authors, it's

571
00:33:23.942 --> 00:33:26.342
my honor to present our recent work

572
00:33:27.202 --> 00:33:30.802
on OncoTwin, a multimodal digital twin

573
00:33:30.862 --> 00:33:34.222
framework for predicting treatment response and

574
00:33:34.482 --> 00:33:38.222
guiding trial design in ALK-rearranged non-small cell lung

575
00:33:38.282 --> 00:33:42.102
cancer. My name is Xu Hui from MD Anderson Cancer

576
00:33:42.162 --> 00:33:42.502
Center.

577
00:33:44.922 --> 00:33:47.722
I have no conflicts of interest to disclose.

578
00:33:48.562 --> 00:33:52.542
First, I want to introduce our BrightStar clinical trial, which

579
00:33:52.602 --> 00:33:56.502
is a phase 2 clinical trial to evaluate the flexibility,

580
00:33:56.602 --> 00:34:00.542
safety, and efficacy of integrating local

581
00:34:00.602 --> 00:34:04.062
consolidation therapy with brigatinib compared with

582
00:34:04.162 --> 00:34:07.852
brigatinib alone in TKI naive or ALK-rearranged

583
00:34:07.922 --> 00:34:09.223
non-small cell lung cancer.

584
00:34:10.882 --> 00:34:14.502
The right panel is the observed progression-free

585
00:34:14.582 --> 00:34:18.502
survival of BrightStar trial. The median PFS is

586
00:34:18.522 --> 00:34:22.422
around 66 months. The survival looks good,

587
00:34:22.922 --> 00:34:23.263
but

588
00:34:24.223 --> 00:34:28.182
since it's a single-arm clinical trial, how do we know the

589
00:34:28.243 --> 00:34:29.842
ALCT benefit or not?

590
00:34:31.223 --> 00:34:35.022
When we extend to all these kinds of single-arm clinical trial,

591
00:34:35.422 --> 00:34:39.062
we miss the control arm. How can we quantify the trial

592
00:34:39.122 --> 00:34:42.682
results? In this work, we aim to solve this issue.

593
00:34:43.842 --> 00:34:47.763
Real-world data always holds great potential to support clinical

594
00:34:47.842 --> 00:34:51.822
trial evidence. Our GEMINI database contains over

595
00:34:51.862 --> 00:34:54.962
16,000 lung cancer patients. Applying

596
00:34:55.942 --> 00:34:59.102
eligibility criteria, we finally identified

597
00:34:59.282 --> 00:35:03.022
103 ALK-rearranged patients from our

598
00:35:03.062 --> 00:35:06.862
real-world database. Crucially, we know none of these

599
00:35:06.922 --> 00:35:08.662
patients received ALCT.

600
00:35:10.162 --> 00:35:13.762
We used these patients to build a prognostic model, then

601
00:35:13.862 --> 00:35:17.382
applied the model to BrightStar trial to estimate these

602
00:35:17.402 --> 00:35:20.682
patients' outcome without ALCT. Since we

603
00:35:20.742 --> 00:35:24.622
simulated the counterfactual trajectory of the exact same

604
00:35:24.682 --> 00:35:27.742
trial patients, we call this a digital twin.

605
00:35:29.762 --> 00:35:33.022
Here we outline our data collection and modeling

606
00:35:33.102 --> 00:35:36.882
framework. We collected the whole body CT images

607
00:35:37.022 --> 00:35:39.282
for panel routine blood test from

608
00:35:40.462 --> 00:35:43.462
both baseline and post-induction time points.

609
00:35:44.122 --> 00:35:47.882
From CT images, we performed whole body 3D annotation

610
00:35:47.942 --> 00:35:51.642
lesion by lesion, and labeled the lesion location also.

611
00:35:52.582 --> 00:35:55.662
The corresponding delta features were also calculated.

612
00:35:56.202 --> 00:35:59.842
Except for these features, we also collected some clinical ready data,

613
00:36:00.502 --> 00:36:04.222
including 2D sum of the longest diameter, we will name

614
00:36:04.362 --> 00:36:07.982
SLD later, TKI type, and clinical demographic

615
00:36:08.062 --> 00:36:11.662
features. By leveraging this data, we constructed two

616
00:36:11.742 --> 00:36:14.942
models. The first, 2D model uses

617
00:36:15.022 --> 00:36:18.682
only clinical ready variables, including

618
00:36:18.802 --> 00:36:22.642
2D SLD, TKI type, and clinical features, making it

619
00:36:22.842 --> 00:36:25.802
straightforward to implement in clinical practice.

620
00:36:26.282 --> 00:36:30.052
The second, 3D model is more comprehensive, incorporating

621
00:36:30.362 --> 00:36:34.072
3D longitudinal whole body tumor burden, longitudinal

622
00:36:34.142 --> 00:36:37.742
routine blood tests, TKI type, and clinical features,

623
00:36:37.922 --> 00:36:41.562
offering a granular characterization of each

624
00:36:41.602 --> 00:36:45.494
patient.We used a hold out

625
00:36:45.654 --> 00:36:47.714
five-fold independent test

626
00:36:51.214 --> 00:36:54.994
scheme to test the prognosis performance of

627
00:36:55.314 --> 00:36:58.954
OncoTwin 2D model. Our results show OncoTwin

628
00:36:59.194 --> 00:37:02.454
2D can realize risk stratification with

629
00:37:02.714 --> 00:37:04.704
significance in overall cohorts.

630
00:37:05.414 --> 00:37:08.914
However, in different TKI

631
00:37:08.994 --> 00:37:12.754
generation subgroups, it holds potential but didn't reach

632
00:37:12.814 --> 00:37:15.394
the statistical significance.

633
00:37:17.654 --> 00:37:21.594
Using the same evaluation strategy, OncoTwin 3D

634
00:37:21.674 --> 00:37:25.663
model achieved a significant risk stratification in both the overall

635
00:37:25.734 --> 00:37:29.114
cohort and each TKI generation subgroup,

636
00:37:30.154 --> 00:37:34.044
demonstrating superior prognostic performance over the 2D model.

637
00:37:36.714 --> 00:37:40.354
Beyond the risk stratification, we further validated our

638
00:37:40.414 --> 00:37:44.194
model's prognosis simulation capability on the OTA-1L

639
00:37:44.254 --> 00:37:45.154
trial cohort.

640
00:37:46.174 --> 00:37:49.774
OTA-1L is a phase III trial comparing two

641
00:37:49.814 --> 00:37:53.134
TKI generations, crizotinib versus

642
00:37:53.254 --> 00:37:56.214
brigatinib, in all career range of lung cancer.

643
00:37:56.624 --> 00:38:00.114
Its long-term results demonstrated a significantly better

644
00:38:00.214 --> 00:38:02.554
progression-free survival with brigatinib.

645
00:38:04.274 --> 00:38:08.254
These trial results were published in the "New England Journal"

646
00:38:08.354 --> 00:38:12.194
in 2018, leading to FDA approval of

647
00:38:12.294 --> 00:38:15.974
brigatinib as the first-line standard of care for all career

648
00:38:16.034 --> 00:38:17.494
range of non-small cell lung cancer.

649
00:38:18.914 --> 00:38:22.614
Applying OncoTwin 2D to the OTA-1L patients, the

650
00:38:22.674 --> 00:38:26.434
model simulated survival closely matched to the observed

651
00:38:26.444 --> 00:38:30.174
trial outcome with no significance in both two

652
00:38:30.454 --> 00:38:34.114
TKI subgroups. That confirms OncoTwin 2D

653
00:38:34.184 --> 00:38:38.074
can replicate the real clinical trial survivals despite the model

654
00:38:38.114 --> 00:38:39.034
is simple.

655
00:38:41.134 --> 00:38:45.054
Building on the successful validation of 2D model, we now

656
00:38:45.134 --> 00:38:48.934
use OncoTwin 3D model and return to the BrightStar

657
00:38:49.054 --> 00:38:51.754
trial to answer our original questions.

658
00:38:53.093 --> 00:38:56.174
Is LCT effective in this single-arm setting?

659
00:38:57.194 --> 00:39:00.394
BrightStar trial totally enrolled 34 patients.

660
00:39:00.774 --> 00:39:04.234
The left table is the patients' baseline characteristics,

661
00:39:05.254 --> 00:39:08.714
of whom 32 received LCT. We applied

662
00:39:08.914 --> 00:39:12.554
OncoTwin 3D to simulate each patient's prognosis

663
00:39:12.674 --> 00:39:16.654
without LCT, directly answering what would have happened to

664
00:39:16.694 --> 00:39:19.274
these patients if they didn't receive LCT.

665
00:39:19.794 --> 00:39:23.674
This allows us to synthesize a natural control arm using the

666
00:39:23.694 --> 00:39:25.794
exact same 32 patients.

667
00:39:26.694 --> 00:39:30.654
Comparing the simulated and observed survival, looking at the

668
00:39:30.694 --> 00:39:34.154
survival curve of the right panel, we found a

669
00:39:34.194 --> 00:39:37.994
significant difference. The solid curve is the actually

670
00:39:38.054 --> 00:39:41.554
observed survival of the trial patients.

671
00:39:41.634 --> 00:39:45.334
The dashed curve is the digital twin simulated survival

672
00:39:45.374 --> 00:39:48.874
without LCT. The results shows a significant

673
00:39:49.014 --> 00:39:52.694
survival benefit with hazard ratio around 2.8

674
00:39:53.254 --> 00:39:55.694
and the log-rank p is significant.

675
00:39:57.054 --> 00:40:00.994
We can therefore answer the clinical questions with more confidence, LCT

676
00:40:01.034 --> 00:40:02.074
should be effective.

677
00:40:03.114 --> 00:40:06.934
But you may ask, how do we know the simulated outcomes are reliable?

678
00:40:07.714 --> 00:40:11.494
To validate this, we performed a propensity score matching using the

679
00:40:11.534 --> 00:40:13.134
OTA-1L cohort. The

680
00:40:14.394 --> 00:40:18.094
propensity score matching derived hazard ratio closely matched our

681
00:40:18.154 --> 00:40:19.374
digital twin estimate,

682
00:40:20.174 --> 00:40:24.114
indirectly confirming the reliability of our synthetic control

683
00:40:24.134 --> 00:40:28.054
arm. However, while our propensity score matching can provide

684
00:40:28.094 --> 00:40:31.354
the supportive evidence for single-arm trial, it has

685
00:40:31.894 --> 00:40:34.554
several limitations, such as

686
00:40:35.374 --> 00:40:39.014
unmeasured confounding bias, group level

687
00:40:39.094 --> 00:40:42.274
inference only, and lack of standardization.

688
00:40:43.574 --> 00:40:46.414
We further show an example in the right panel.

689
00:40:46.754 --> 00:40:49.774
These two patients, they have similar clinical

690
00:40:49.854 --> 00:40:53.154
characterizations, but their outcomes were totally different.

691
00:40:55.074 --> 00:40:58.934
The right side patient progressed within

692
00:40:58.994 --> 00:41:02.594
five months, while the left side patient remained

693
00:41:02.603 --> 00:41:06.154
progression free for over 16 months.

694
00:41:06.374 --> 00:41:09.854
But our digital twin model can capture this heterogeneity,

695
00:41:11.454 --> 00:41:12.294
enable

696
00:41:13.174 --> 00:41:17.154
early clinical insights and provided individual outcome prediction.

697
00:41:19.594 --> 00:41:23.514
We further compare traditional random control trial,

698
00:41:23.614 --> 00:41:27.154
propensity score matching, and digital twin as control arm strategies.

699
00:41:27.694 --> 00:41:31.254
Random control trial is the golden standard but is

700
00:41:31.474 --> 00:41:35.274
slow, expensive, and hard to generalize to real-world

701
00:41:35.354 --> 00:41:39.214
patients. Propensity score matching is more practical but is

702
00:41:39.254 --> 00:41:41.754
still limited by covariate bias and

703
00:41:42.654 --> 00:41:46.174
only for group level inference. The digital twin overcomes

704
00:41:46.334 --> 00:41:50.194
both, is fast, cost efficient, and

705
00:41:50.314 --> 00:41:53.894
allows individual prediction, making it the most viable

706
00:41:53.934 --> 00:41:55.714
approach for single-arm trials.

707
00:41:57.934 --> 00:42:01.394
Beyond the control arm simulation, the digital twin has other

708
00:42:01.454 --> 00:42:04.834
applications including individual survival trajectory

709
00:42:04.874 --> 00:42:05.494
prediction,

710
00:42:06.414 --> 00:42:10.234
individual treatment effect estimation, and using

711
00:42:10.354 --> 00:42:13.594
simulation-based resampling to assess patient

712
00:42:14.174 --> 00:42:17.834
enrollment size, which could support the design of next

713
00:42:17.934 --> 00:42:18.714
phase trial.

714
00:42:20.734 --> 00:42:24.474
In conclusion, we introduced a digital twin framework

715
00:42:24.634 --> 00:42:27.994
that models individual treatment trajectories use

716
00:42:28.074 --> 00:42:31.694
multimodal data in all career range of the lung small cell lung

717
00:42:31.774 --> 00:42:35.694
cancer. Its application in the phase II BrightStar trial

718
00:42:35.754 --> 00:42:39.554
demonstrated how retrospective real-world data can

719
00:42:39.614 --> 00:42:43.374
inform prospective trial design through AI model.

720
00:42:44.354 --> 00:42:48.094
Also, this framework serves as a blueprint extensible to

721
00:42:48.594 --> 00:42:49.654
other cancer types.

